location.locality: Steese Highway just past junction to Circle Hot Springs

mediaNotes: Adult and chick calls. Chick calls are a high piping. All other calls are adults. 2 adults and 5 chicks present. One adult with 2 chicks and one with 3. Could be a mated pair. Response to playback: Approach. Other Behaviors: Emit Alarm, Establish Parent Young Contact, Beg, Care For Young, Social Context: Family. Habitat: Coniferous Forest, Pond.

location.name: Two Moose Lake, Dempster Highway KM104

mediaNotes: duet song from a pair of birds on a medium-sized lake surrounded by fairly dry alpine tundra. One of the birds is barely audible over the wind; the one that is loud was swimming with its cheek feathers fluffed out while singing.
Calls in apparent alarm to my presence from a pair of birds at the edge of a large lake.

NOTES: A) A COPULATION SEQUENCE: MALE ON WATER; FEMALE ON A FLOATING MAT OF VEGETATION; MALE SWIMS TOWARD FEMALE GIVING HIGH-PITCHED NOTES; FEMALE RESPONDS WITH LOWER TRIAD NOTES; MALE EMERGES AND MOUNTS GIVING LOUDEST NOTES; THEN JUMPS OFF INTO WATER; BOTH BIRDS PREEN.   B) CALLS WHILE ON WATER. Other Behaviors: Copulate, Court, Mate.

location.name: Long Lake Road, Kamloops, British Columbia, CA (50.785, -120.396)

mediaNotes: adult calls and soft chick begging calls
Other Behaviors: Court. Habitat: Wetland, Freshwater.
Song/call series from a dull breeding plumage bird out on the lake.

NOTES: a pair on a pothole. Male on water, female on a possible nest outcrop of vegetation. Copulation sequence; male swims toward female giving high-pitched notes, female responds with lower, triad notes, male emerges and mounts female, giving loudest sequence then jumps off with a splash into water. Both birds preen.HPF@120hz. LNS. Other Behaviors: Copulate. Habitat: Lake, Pond.
Horned Grebe calling (while on water) to another, after having resurfaced from foraging. Heard at 2s and 11s
There were 5 other HOGR further out from the beach. This one was by himself and began to call periodically. The 5 disappeared, but this poor guy kept swimming an d calling.

The recording has several periods of vocalization separated by substantial silences, beginning with a single weak call at 3s and ending with a series of 12 calls.  The lone grebe remained in the centre of a small slough, moving little, with some head bobbing.  There is a lot of competing bird song.
